      {
        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "### Why? The Chelate Effect\n\nThis dramatic difference is the textbook **chelate effect**. Ethylenediamine (en) is a bidentate ligand: its two –NH₂ groups simultaneously coordinate to Ni²⁺, forming a stable five-membered chelate ring. This confers:\n\n1. **Entropic advantage** — binding one en molecule releases fewer degrees of freedom than binding two separate NH₃ molecules to occupy the same two coordination sites. The ΔS data confirm this: at I = 0.1 M, ΔS(Ni–en) = +9.2 J mol⁻¹ K⁻¹ vs. ΔS(Ni–NH₃) ≈ +1.7 J mol⁻¹ K⁻¹.\n2. **Geometric preorganization** — once one –NH₂ of en is bound, the second is held in close proximity, making ring closure highly favorable.\n\nThe chelate effect is why polydentate ligands like EDTA (hexadentate) are used in industrial metal sequestration and analytical chemistry — their log K values can exceed 18 for Ni²⁺, dwarfing even en.\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46 (metal_112 = Ni²⁺, ligand_10103 = NH₃, ligand_7029 = en; beta_def_812 = ML)*",
